@startuml
title Viaverse Security / Privacy / Compliance — Component Diagram

component "KMP / Next.js Client\nsecure storage\nconsent UI\nprivacy center" as Client
component "AWS Edge\nWAF\nTLS\nrate limit\nCDN rules" as Edge
component "API Gateway\nJWT validation\ncorrelationId\nrequest policy" as Gateway
component "identity-service\nOTP/social login\nJWT/refresh\ncapabilities\nadmin MFA" as Identity
component "privacy-service\nconsent\nDSAR\nretention\ndata map" as Privacy
component "Domain Services\npolicy enforcement\nownership checks\nredaction" as Services
component "External Secrets + KMS\nsecret sync\nencryption keys\nrotation" as Secrets
component "audit-service\nsensitive access\nadmin actions\nDSAR receipts" as Audit
database "PostgreSQL / Cassandra\nrow ownership\nretention tags\nencrypted fields" as DB
queue "Kafka / Outbox\nConsentChanged\nDataDeleted\nSecurityIncidentRaised" as Kafka
component "Security Monitoring\nanomaly\nincident queue\nalerts" as Monitor

Client --> Edge : HTTPS
Edge --> Gateway : forward
Gateway --> Identity : token/introspection
Gateway --> Services : authorized request
Services --> DB : persist/read
Services --> Secrets : secret/key usage
Services --> Audit : sensitive audit
Privacy --> Services : DSAR/retention commands
Privacy --> Kafka : privacy events
Audit --> Monitor : risk signals
Identity --> Kafka : auth/security events

note bottom
Security is not one service.
Edge, gateway, identity, domain policies, secrets, audit,
privacy and monitoring work as layered controls.
end note
@enduml
